<F P=100> UNITED KINGDOM </F>
<H3> <TI>   Group Urges Clinton To Stop IRA Intimidation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1201130394 London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 1157 GMT 12 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1201130394 </F>
<F P=104>  London PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Ian Graham, PRESS ASSOCIATION] </F>
  [Text] President Bill Clinton was today urged to demand 
that the IRA stopped exiling people from Northern Ireland 
before lifting the ban on Sinn Fein President Gerry Adams 
entering the United States. 
  The Families Against Intimidation and Terror [FAIT] handed 
in 
a letter at the American Consulate in Belfast pressing the 
president to make any lifting of the ban conditional on Mr. 
Adams using his influence to stop the terrorists banishing 
people under threat of death. 
  The organisation urged Mr. Clinton to write to Mr. Adams 
"asking him to use his considerable influence with the IRA to 
have this practice stopped and the existing expulsions lifted, 
so that those living in exile may return." 
  It asked him to bring the plight of those exiled by the 
terrorists to the attention of the Senate "urging them to lift 
the ban on Mr. Adams as a matter of urgency, as soon as the 
Republican movement lift the expulsion orders on Irish men and 
women." 
  In the past year alone FAIT has dealt with 35 cases of 
forced 
expulsion involving 63 people -- 28 individuals and seven entire 
families. 

</TEXT>

