<H3> <TI>   Bundesbank Announces Money Supply Growth </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0701151794 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1410 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0701151794 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Frankfurt/Main (DDP/ADN) -- After seasonal 
adjustment, the money supply, M3, rose in November by 7.2 
percent in comparison with the fourth quarter of 1992. This was 
announced by the Bundesbank in Frankfurt am Main on Friday [7 
January]. In October the rate was 6.9 percent. 
  Frankfurt's money traders reacted calmly to the 
announcement. 
The Bundesbank will adhere to its policy of relaxation of 
interest rates, it is said in banking circles. An economist 
with the Commerzbank said: "Hopes remain for an early reduction 
in base rates." The Bundesbank stressed that it is seeking 
growth in the money supply of between 4 and 6 percent in 1994. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

