<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Economic Institute Pessimistic About 1994 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0801173094 Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE in German 
7 Jan 94 p 13 </F>

<F P=103> AU0801173094 </F>
<F P=104>  Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report signed "enn": "DIW Does Not Expect Fast Upswing"] </F>
  [Text] Berlin, 6 Jan -- The German Institute for Economic 
Research (DIW) has made a forecast for 1994 that is clearly more 
pessimistic than those of all the other German institutes. The 
Berlin-based research institute does not expect a quick economic 
upswing. On Thursday [6 January], the DIW said that a gradual 
upward trend can be expected to start in summer, at the 
earliest. The recession has not yet been overcome. German 
economic policy is characterized by illusions and wrong 
assessments in this area, the DIW said. In western Germany, the 
GNP is expected to decline by an estimated 0.5 percent this 
year. The number of unemployed in eastern and western Germany 
will go up to a total of some 4 million. In the DIW 
researchers' view, the debate about Germany as a business 
location overrates the alleged crisis of costs faced by German 
companies. No study has yet been able to prove that German 
industry has a severe lack of international competitiveness. 
The decline in profits is a "phenomenon exclusively due to 
economic cycles." Some impetus from abroad is possible; but 
export hopes can refer only to overseas markets. Besides, the 
European countries can only overcome the recession "marching in 
step." The role monetary policy plays in the development of 
recession is underestimated. Relaxing monetary policy is the 
key to an increase in investments. In the DIW's opinion, 
short-term and long-term interest rates should be approximately 
2 percentage points apart. 
  According to the DIW, the economic policy debate 
concentrates 
too much on wage policy. "Cutting wages" alone is a defensive 
strategy that is unlikely to succeed. This year, the institute 
expects moderate wage settlements "in the region of 2 percent." 
In 1996, wage increases could return to some 4 percent, a rate 
that will be appropriate in the medium term. Private 
consumption will go down by some 1.5 percent in 1994, which will 
have an enormous effect on the economy. The government's 
envisaged austerity measures will also have a restrictive impact 
on the economy. Considering this, 1994 is an unsuitable time 
for consolidating public budgets, the DIW said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

