<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Working Group Suggests Bundeswehr Savings Plan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1001171294 Hamburg DER SPIEGEL in German 10 Jan 94 p 16 </F>
<F P=103> AU1001171294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DER SPIEGEL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Saving Must Pay Off"] </F>
  [Text] The Bundeswehr could save an estimated 3.8 billion 
German marks [DM] per year just through rationalization. This 
is indicated in a confidential interim report by an internal 
Defense Ministry working group. The savings, which correspond 
to 10 percent of the current operational expenditures of the 
armed forces, are, however, only possible "in the long run." A 
new system for monitoring costs and performance must be 
established. In the view of the working group, first 
investments of approximately DM100 million are necessary for 
this purpose -- for new computers, for instance. Under the 
slogan of "Saving must pay off," all soldiers should be 
encouraged to participate in the "constant identification of 
rationalization potential." "As far as it is useful and 
possible," logistical tasks are to be transferred to private 
companies. In addition, the working group, which consists of 
military officers and representatives of civilian consulting 
companies, suggests that armament projects should be supervised 
more strictly. Tighter management could reduce procurement 
costs by approximately DM400 million per year. In 1993, the 
Defense Ministry spent almost DM7 billion on weapons and 
ammunition. 

</TEXT>

