<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aho Wants Clarification of Partnership for Peace </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1201114994 Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network in Finnish 
1000 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1201114994 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Finnish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Esko Aho is critical of the debate 
conducted in Finland about NATO's Partnership for Peace 
initiative. According to Aho, in the debate at home, Finland has 
been placed in the same position as the member countries of the 
former Warsaw Treaty. After talks with Dutch Prime Minister 
Ruud Lubbers, Aho's interpretation was that the Partnership for 
Peace initiative serves primarily the former socialist countries 
of Eastern Europe, and an open invitation has been extended to 
the other CSCE countries merely in the name of impartiality. 
  Aho thought that the countries that had sought membership in 
the European Union could progress to become observer or full 
members of the Union's defense system, the Western European 
Union, and that way possibly further into NATO membership. Aho 
said that the Finnish Government intends to ask for 
clarification of what NATO means by Partnership for Peace. 

</TEXT>

