<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Sweden </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Supports NATO `Warning' to Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1101191494 Paris AFP in English 1906 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1101191494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Stockholm, Jan 11 (AFP) -- A decision by NATO 
leaders to use air power in support of UN forces in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina may motivate the fighting parties to return 
to the negotiating table, Swedish Foreign Minister Margaretha af 
Ugglas said Tuesday [11 January]. 
  "It is good that NATO is now sharpening its tone against the 
Bosnian Serbs. The threat of air attacks is a very sharp 
warning that the Serbs ought to take seriously," she said. 
  "The situation has worsened in recent weeks. It is a natural 
frustration that is now being expressed by the NATO countries," 
she commented. 
  Af Ugglas, the former chairwoman of the Conference on 
Security and Cooperation in Europe, would not say whether she 
believes the North Atlantic Treaty Organization's threat issued 
Tuesday at a summit in Brussels would be carried out to lift the 
siege on threatened areas in Bosnia. 
  "That is a decision that must be taken by the UN's local 
military commanders and the UN secretary general," she concluded. 

</TEXT>

