<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ankara Reportedly Takes Measures Against Moscow, Athens </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1101191394 Istanbul HURRIYET in Turkish 8 Jan 94 p 18 </F>
<F P=103> NC1101191394 </F>
<F P=104>  Istanbul HURRIYET </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Selin Caglayan: "Military Measures Against </F>
Moscow and Athens"] 
  [Text] Ankara--It has been reported that Turkey has taken 
military measures to deal with any possible threat, particularly 
from Moscow and Athens. The officials have said that Turkey has 
been worried by Russia's move to quickly convert its cumbersome 
military forces into an army capable of taking swift action and 
by the steps Greece has taken in the same direction. 
  Stressing that Turkey is also restructuring its military 
forces, the officials asserted: "An effort is being made to 
establish a smaller army that will be capable of taking quick 
action with very high fire power." 
  It has been ascertained that the summit held on security 
discussed the threat to Turkey the day before yesterday. It 
also agreed on the need to convert the Turkish Army into a 
military force capable of taking quick action. There was a 
decision to strengthen the Turkish Armed Forces when the cold 
war ended, but that decision was not pursued. 
  Recalling that Turkey has not made significant changes in 
its 
threat concept for many years, several sources said that the 
threat to Turkey comes from all sides -- from the north, south, 
east, and west. That, they said, was also the case in the past. 
<H5>  Anxiety Caused by Russia </H5>
  The Turkish experts on strategy have been worried by 
Russia's 
recent move to change its doctrine and base several of its air 
force units in the southern part of the Caucasus. Meanwhile, 
the Papandreou Government's disclosure that Cyprus and the 
Aegean Sea are "Hellenic regions" has created a tense atmosphere 
between Ankara and Athens. Greece's claim that it has the right 
to fortify the Greek islands in the eastern part of the Aegean 
Sea has compelled Ankara to take certain measures. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

