<F P=100> BENELUX COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Belgium </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dehaene: Government Will Not Outlaw PKK </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101161894 Brussels Radio Vlaanderen International in 
English 1400 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1101161894 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels Radio Vlaanderen International </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] During the NATO summit, Prime Minister Dehaene has 
repeated that Belgium does not intend to outlaw the Kurdish 
nationalist PKK [Workers Party of Kurdistan] party, but Belgium 
does condemn the terrorist activities of the PKK. Dehaene had a 
short talk with his Turkish colleague Ciller at the summit. 
  Turkey had asked Belgium to ban the PKK after the recent 
Turkish-Kurdish riots in Brussels. Belgium, however, is 
sticking to its own policy. Dehaene said that the government 
would decide itself how to deal with problems here. He asked 
the Turkish premier to solve the problems between the Turkish 
Government and Kurdish minority through negotiation, and pointed 
out that Belgium had solved its community problems peacefully. 

</TEXT>

