<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Belgium's Dehaene Comments on NATO's Bosnia Decision </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101181194 Brussels La Une Radio Network in French 1700 
GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1101181194 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels La Une Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] The NATO summit ended late this afternoon. The 
heads of state and government of the military alliance decided 
to express their concern about the conflict in former 
Yugoslavia. [passage omitted] 
  Several delegations, including Belgium's, refrained from 
setting a timetable for intervention, recalling that it is not 
up to NATO to launch air strikes, since operations in the area 
are made at the request of the United Nations. Here is Prime 
Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene speaking in an interview with Willy 
van der Vort: 
  [Begin Dehaene recording] Let us say that NATO has clearly 
confirmed its willingness and its support for intervention, but 
that these are UN actions, and the decision has to be taken by 
the United Nations. So, contrary to the impression that might 
have been given after the statement by the secretary general 
yesterday evening, there is no misunderstanding between the 
United Nations and NATO. What NATO is putting forward today are 
actions to be implemented within the United Nations, and the 
final decision will be taken by the United Nations. 
  The Serbs said yesterday that air intervention against their 
positions in Bosnia could have serious consequences. We have to 
keep this in mind, but I think at the same time that to remain 
without action is fraught with another danger, namely that the 
Serbs will think they can do what they like. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

