<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO Supports Russian Reform, Concerned on Caucasus </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1101130294 Paris AFP in English 1110 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1101130294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, Jan 11 (AFP) -- The North Atlantic Treaty 
Organisation on Tuesday [11 January] encouraged Russian reforms 
but expressed concern about continuing fighting and instability 
in the republics on Russia's southern rim. 
  In a statement issued at the end of a two-day NATO summit, 
the 16 nations reaffirmed support for political and economic 
reforms pursued by President Boris Yeltsin, despite the 
emergence of a strong challenge from extreme nationalists in the 
new parliament. 
  The December 12 Russian elections and adoption of a new 
constitution conferring executive powers on the president marked 
"a major step forward in the establishment of framework for the 
development of durable democratic institutions. 
  "We further welcome the Russian government's firm commitment 
to democratic and market reform and to a reformist foreign 
policy. These are important for security and stability in 
Europe. We believe that an indepednent, democratic, stable and 
nuclear-weapons free Ukraine would likewise contribute to 
security and stability. 
  "We will continue to encourage and support the reform 
processes in both countries and to develop cooperation with 
them, as with other countries in Central and East Europe," NATO 
said. 
  But the communique went on: "The situation in southern 
Caucasus continues to be of special concern," referring mainly 
to Armenia's bitter territorial struggle with Azerbaijan over 
Armenian-dominated Nagorno-Karabakh. 
  "We condemn the use of force for territorial gains. Respect 
for the territorial integrity, independence and sovereignty of 
Armenia, Azerbaijan and Georgia is essential to the 
establishment of peace, stability and cooperation in the region." 
  "We call upon all states to join international efforts under 
the aegis of the United Nations and the CSCE (Conference on 
Security and Cooperation in Europe) aimed at solving existing 
problems." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

