<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   UK's Major on Importance of NATO-Russian Relationship </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101132294 London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 1234 GMT 11 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1101132294 </F>
<F P=104>  London PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mr. Major revealed he will travel to Moscow to meet 
President Boris Yeltsin in the next few weeks in addition to 
plans to visit Washington late next month. 
  "It is very important to build up our relationship with the 
democratic leaders in Russia as well as Central and East 
Europe," he said. 
  "They are our friends. They have new and democratic 
institutions and they have liberalised their economies. 
  "Russia has a hugely important part to play in the world. 
The relationship between Russia and NATO can only be to the 
benefit of both sides. We have been seeking at this meeting to 
build a stable framework for the most profound changes in modern 
history." 
  Mr. Major went to meet NATO military chiefs, including the 
Supreme Allied Commander Europe, General George Joulwan, and the 
chairman of the Military Committee, Field Marshal Sir Dick 
Vincent. 
  He wanted to hear their advice about what action was 
feasible 
in Bosnia and how the summit's decisions to open NATO doors to 
the East could be implemented. 

</TEXT>

