<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   French Leaders Comment on Bosnia Situation, Summit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Says Force To Be Used </H4>
<F P=102> LD1101153694 Paris France-2 Television Network in French 
1200 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1101153694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris France-2 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] At the NATO summit in Brussels, the Atlantic 
alliance has threatened again to use air power in Bosnia 
following the initiative of the French and the British. In 
concrete terms, the aim is to prevent the strangulation of 
Sarajevo and to unblock Srebrenica, as well as Tuzla airport. 
Laurent Boussie reports: 
  [Boussie] The French are satisfied. Bosnia, which was not on 
the agenda of this summit, was in fact at the core of the talks. 
The signature of the Americans, their commitment to support the 
European peace plan, the contribution by the 16 countries of the 
alliance to the implementation of this plan, and their support 
to the United Nations for its action in Bosnia are all positive 
elements that were not on the agenda at the beginning of this 
summit. 
  There is a firm commitment behind these diplomatic gestures: 
In two specific cases, Srebrenica and Tuzla, the use of force is 
not only being considered, it is almost planned. 
  [Begin Juppe recording] The Twelve of the European Union 
[EU] 
have requested it [?the use of force] on several occasions, and 
I did the same myself strongly when I met Mr. Karadzic in 
Geneva, and later on in Brussels; the Serbs have refused. We 
are now deciding to go ahead all the same. [end recording] 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

