<F P=100> AUSTRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Haider Denies Report </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1101143594 Vienna DER STANDARD in German 11 Jan 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> AU1101143594 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna DER STANDARD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "`No Contacts With Neo-Nazis' -- </F>
Haider's Spokesman Announces Legal Action'"] 
  [Text] Vienna -- Joerg Haider, Freedom Party of Austria 
[FPOe] chairman, does not even want to comment on statements 
former neo-Nazi Ingo Hasselbach made in an interview with DER 
STANDARD. Hasselbach had said that Haider has had personal 
contact with the Austrian neo-Nazi scene. FPOe Press Spokesman 
Peter Westenthaler: "This is absolute nonsense." FPOe Secretary 
General Karl-Heinz Grasser said there never has been any contact 
between Haider and the two neo-Nazis Gottfried Kuessel and 
Walter Ochensberger. Grasser also said that the FPOe would take 
legal action against DER STANDARD and Hasselbach. 
  However, the FPOe did not object to Hasselbach's book 
entitled Die Abrechnung [Settling of Accounts], where 
Kuessel speaks of links between neo-Nazis and the FPOe. FPOe 
Secretary General Grasser called Hasselbach's statements a 
"complete web of lies." 
  Reinhart Rohr, Social Democratic Party of Austria [SPOe] 
chairman for Carinthia, sees these reports in a different light. 
"If Hasselbach's allegations are true," it becomes clear why 
Haider should consider the investigations into the letter-bomb 
attacks [carried out in Austria last December] "hostile to the 
state." 
  FPOe Deputy Helmut Prasch criticized the fact that the SPOe 
seems to attach greater importance to the statement of a 
neo-Nazi than to "statements by a democratically elected 
Austrian politician." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

