<F P=100> IRELAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Iran's Foreign Minister Velayati Begins Dublin Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   To Attend Iranian-Irish Commission </H4>
<F P=102> LD1101213094 Tehran IRNA in English 1830 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1101213094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] London, Jan. 11, IRNA -- Iran's foreign minister, 
'Ali Akbar Velayati, was due to arrive in Dublin Tuesday [11 
January] night to attend the second joint economic commission 
with Ireland. 
  During his two-day stay in the Irish capital, the Iranian 
minister is scheduled to hold talks with Ireland's President 
Mary Robinson, Prime Minister Albert Reynolds, Foreign Minister 
Dick Spring, and various other senior officials in a hectic 
timetable. 
  The joint commission was first established in April 1992, 
during a visit by the then Irish foreign minister, David 
Andrews, when a memorandum of understanding for political and 
economic cooperation was signed by the two countries. 
  In April last year, Iran's Deputy Foreign Minister for 
Euro-American Affairs Mahmud Va'ezi paved the way for the 
holding of the second commission, which was original scheduled 
for November but delayed until this month. 
  Velayati's visit is expected to culminate in the inking of a 
further cooperation agreement, in such areas as electronics, 
computer technology, scientific and cultural exchanges, in which 
Ireland has already expressed its interest. 

</TEXT>

