<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Balladur Meets With Saudi `Businessman' Prince </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1201200294 Paris AFP in English 1921 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1201200294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, Jan 12 (AFP) -- French Prime Minister 
Edouard Balladur held talks on bilateral cooperation Wednesday 
[12 January] with Prince Mohammad Bin-Fahd, son of Saudi 
Arabia's King Fahd, French officials said. 
  The 40-minute meeting with the man touted as the Saudi 
regime's "businessman" covered political, economic, energy, and 
defence issues, the officials said. 
  It took place three days after Balladur returned from a trip 
to Saudi Arabia, during which the two countries agreed to create 
a bilateral commission of experts on financing maintenance of 
French military equipment sold to the Arab state. 
  But the French premier failed to seal hoped-for business 
deals during his stay. 
  A spokesman for Balladur said the meeting had "given a major 
boost" to bilateral relations. 
  The prince, who is the governor of Saudi Arabia's Eastern 
Province, had talks with France's defence and interior ministers 
Tuesday. 
  He was also due to meet President Francois Mitterand later 
Wednesday. 

</TEXT>

