<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   No-Confidence Motion Shows Parliamentary Splits </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301105994 Rome RAI Uno Television Network in Italian 1000 
GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1301105994 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome RAI Uno Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Italian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] The debate on the no-confidence motion presented 
against the government of [Carlo Azeglio] Ciampi is continuing 
in the Chamber of Deputies. Let us link up with Francesco 
Pionati. 
  [Pionati] Yes, the debate is taking place in a confused 
atmosphere. At the end of this morning, Ciampi will go to the 
Quirinale Palace [President's office] in order to hand his 
resignation to the Head of State [Oscar Luigi Scalfaro], who 
then has the task of dissolving the chambers and calling fresh 
elections. 
  This morning the differences between the ruling coalition 
parties, that want the legislature to continue -- a view 
supported by [Savino Melillo] from the Liberal Party and by 
[Enrico] Ferri from the Social Democratic Party who both spoke 
this morning, and the opposition parties that, on the other 
hand, want the chambers dissolved and elections to take place by 
the end of March, became apparent once again. [passage omitted] 
  [Giorgio] Napolitano and Ciampi will be the last two to 
speak 
at the debate. At 1200, there will be a meeting of the 
political groups making up the ruling coalition, which want to 
propose a confidence motion in the government. However, this 
proposal now seems out of the question. So all in all, the 
debate is proceeding in this climate of confusion. 

</TEXT>

