<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Welcomes Clinton's Personal Interest </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1201150594 Nicosia CYPRUS NEWS AGENCY in English 1437 GMT 
12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1201150594 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia CYPRUS NEWS AGENCY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Nicosia, Jan 12 (CNA)--The Cyprus government 
welcomes the fact that U.S. President Bill Clinton will 
personally handle the Cyprus problem, government spokesman 
Ioannis Kasoulidhis said here Wednesday [12 January]. 
  Clinton pledged to get personally involved immediately after 
the conclusion of his European tour this week. He made the 
pledge during a meeting with Greek Prime Minister Andreas 
Papandreou and European Commission President Jacques Delors at 
the sidelines of the NATO summit in Brussels yesterday. 
  Kasoulidhis stated "the Cyprus government welcomes the fact 
that President Clinton, personally, and this is a great positive 
development for Cyprus, will handle the Cyprus problem." 
  He added the Greek Cypriot side should also think hard "as 
to 
the way we should responsibly handle our sincere objectives for 
a just and workable Cyprus settlement." 
  Asked whether President Glavkos Kliridhis was briefed on 
what 
exactly was stated by President Clinton, Kasoulidhis replied he 
based his statements on press reports from Brussels. 
  He said the government was in touch with the American State 
Department special Cyprus coordinator and the U.S. Embassy in 
Cyprus and no further contacts between the Cyprus and U.S. 
presidents were being fixed. 

</TEXT>

