<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kliridhis Counters Opposition on Confidence-Building </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1201163594 Nicosia O FILELEVTHEROS in Greek 12 Jan 94 pp 
1, 9 </F>

<F P=103> NC1201163594 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia O FILELEVTHEROS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Stavros Angelidhis] </F>
  [Excerpt] President Glavkos Kliridhis is avoiding calling 
a meeting of the National Council to discuss the substance of 
the confidence-building measures so that the cards of the Greek 
Cypriot side are not revealed before the Turkish side responds. 
Government Spokesman Ioannis Kasoulidhis made the above 
statement, arguing that nothing at the National Council meetings 
remains secret. However, in an attempt to lessen the pressure 
from AKEL [Restorative Party of the Working People] and EDEK 
[United Democratic Union of Cyprus] for an immediate convening 
of the National Council -- a view shared by DIKO [Democratic 
Party] Parliamentary Representative Tasos Papadhopoulos -- the 
president has decided to call the leaders of the four parties 
participating in the National Council to hold separate meetings 
for a "discussion of the latest developments in the Cyprus 
issue." Yesterday, the president met DIKO Chairman Spiros 
Kiprianou and today will meet Democratic Rally Chairman Ioannis 
Matsis, AKEL General Secretary Dhimitrios Khristofias and EDEK 
Chairman Vasos Lissaridhis. 
  DIKO Chairman Kiprianou told O FILELEVTHEROS that during the 
meeting they had a general discussion of the latest developments 
concerning the Cyprus issue with special reference to the 
confidence-building measures and the reports of the UN experts 
on these measures. Kiprianou stressed that DIKO categorically 
rejects the proposed confidence-building measures and added that 
the reports of the UN experts give another, clearer picture of 
how dangerous these measures are. 
  Kiprianou added that the president had told him that he is 
not committed by the reports of the UN experts, and that he will 
wait for the response of the Turkish side on the three documents 
of the UN secretary general on the confidence-building measures. 
  For its part, EDEK followed the call of AKEL's General 
Secretary Khristofias Monday and repeated its demand for the 
immediate convening of the National Council, "so that the 
institution does not become obsolete" and questioned whether we 
can reach a solution without discussing the issue. EDEK claims 
that the confidence-building measures constitute a solution much 
worse than the current situation because they provide for two 
separate states, and have our own signature on it. 
  EDEK's statement notes that the UN experts' report gives a 
vivid picture of how destructive the confidence-building 
measures are. It also notes that: "Instead of realizing the 
decline that our national issue has undergone, the government 
continues to declare that it is ready to accept the 
confidence-building measures and that the only remaining issue 
in order to begin the dialogue is the Turkish side's acceptance. 
How can the government follow this line despite the opposite 
position being taken by all parties?" [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

