<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Satisfied With Results of NATO Summit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1201132894 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1230 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1201132894 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Government spokesman Evangelos Venizelos today 
expressed the government's satisfaction with the results of the 
NATO summit in Brussels. Venizelos highlighted that Prime 
Minister Andreas Papandreou had the opportunity, at the highest 
level, to detail the positions of the European Union and those 
of the Greek Government on the big national issues of Skopje and 
Cyprus. 
  The spokesman regretted the grumbling and fabricated, as he 
put it, criticism by the opposition, which is implementing a 
strange policy that is out of place following the NATO summit. 
  In a statement on the results of the prime minister's 
contacts in Brussels, New Democracy discussed a lost 
opportunity. Political Spring also issued a statement claiming 
that the lack of a specific result on the Skopje issue indicates 
the prime minister's failure in his meeting with U.S. President 
Bill Clinton. Replying to the New Democracy and Political 
Spring statements, the government spokesman said among other 
things that the opposition stance unfortunately doesn't match 
the circumstances and shows ignorance regarding developments in 
Brussels and the relevant diplomatic procedures. 

</TEXT>

