<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leotard: New Bosnian Plans Require NATO Air Support </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1301135894 Paris AFP in English 1337 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1301135894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, Jan 13 (AFP) -- United Nations peacekeepers 
in Bosnia-Herzegovina will face greater "risks in the near 
future", French Defence Minister Francois Leotard said here on 
Thursday [13 January]. 
  Leotard was referring to UN plans to reopen the airport at 
the Moslem enclave of Tuzla and to relieve Canadian troops 
blocked in the Srebrenica enclave. 
  Leotard told journalists that if no action was taken, "the 
risks will be even greater if we refuse to carry out the 
essential task of our armies, which is protection of human 
dignity." 
  At Tuzla, the minister said, Swedish peacekeepers "need a 
Danish unit with heavy Leopard tanks and communications systems" 
to allow the airport to be reopened. Effective air support from 
NATO (North Atlantic Treaty Organisation) warplanes was also 
needed, he said. 
  The 12 tanks are at present at Pancevo, near Belgrade. They 
will have to skirt Bosnia to the west and be shipped to Split 
before reaching Tuzla by road, an informed source said. 
  Earlier Leotard told the National Assembly's defence 
committee that starting the Tuzla and Srebrenica operations 
depended on UN Secretary-General Butrus Butrus-Ghali who on 
Thursday was due to meet his representative for former 
Yugoslavia, Yasushi Akashi. 
  A parliamentary sources said that plans were underway for a 
relief corridor between the Dalmatian coast and the capital, 
Sarajevo. 
  Meanwhile in Belgrade, Bosnian Serb chief of staff General 
Manojlo Milovanovic warned that NATO air strikes against Bosnian 
Serb positions would directly threaten the UN Protection Force. 
  In an interview in Thursday's POLITIKA paper, he said: "Let 
them bomb, but by doing so they put the UNPROFOR [United Nations 
Protection Forces] units directly in danger, to say nothing of 
the Croat and Moslem forces in direct contact with the Serb 
forces on all the fronts in Bosnia-Herzegovina." 

</TEXT>

