<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dissolution of Parliament Expected 14 Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301182694 Rome RAI Uno Television Network in Italian 1800 
GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1301182694 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome RAI Uno Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Italian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] [passage omitted] We are clearly drawing closer 
to the early dissolution of the chambers of parliament and the 
consequent general election. If anyone still had any doubts, 
then those doubts were removed a short time ago -- half an hour 
ago -- by a communique from the Quirinale [president's office]. 
The communique says: In accordance with Article 88 of the 
Constitution, tomorrow morning President Scalfaro will receive 
Senate Speaker Spadolini at the Quirinale at 1130, and he will 
receive [Chamber of Deputies Speaker] Napolitano at 1700 that 
afternoon. [passage omitted] 
  The Quirinale's communique says, I repeat: In accordance 
with Article 88. This is the article concerned with the early 
dissolution of the chambers of parliament, and it stipulates 
that the president should consult with the Senate speaker first 
and then with the Chamber of Deputies speaker before proceeding 
to dissolve parliament. The chambers should be dissolved by 
Sunday [16 January], when [President] Scalfaro will then set 
aside his reservations about Prime Minister Carlo Azeglio 
Ciampi's resignation. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

