<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Political Leaders React to Ciampi's Resignation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301203794 Rome RAI Due Television Network in Italian 1845 
GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1301203794 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome RAI Due Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Italian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Speakers identified by caption] </F>
  [Text] This, the 11th legislature, is closing amid anger 
and satisfaction. Most of those disappointed are to be found in 
what was the four-party coalition, while some of the harshest 
reactions have come from the Christian Democrats [DC]. [DC 
leader Mino] Martinazzoli said the government has had a short 
life. He wanted elections to be held in June. Guido 
Dell'Aquila has carried out some interviews: 
  [Begin recording] [Gerardo Bianco, DC spokesman in the 
Chamber of Deputies] I was not expecting this outcome because 
the position taken in parliament by the majority parties 
reconfirmed confidence in the government. In other words, 
Ciampi and his government still have a parliamentary majority, 
so the justification for his resignation has origins outside 
parliament. 
  [Marco Pannella, Radical leader] The country knows that 
everything is once again in the hands of the institutional 
authorities, which certainly offers a wealth of wisdom and 
honesty to the whole country. 
  [Achille Occhetto, Democratic Party of the Left leader] 
Today's action is important because it is the only pacifying 
action which can be implemented in our country. It gives 
citizens the instrument of a parliament which truly represents 
the new Italy and hopefully a government with progressive forces 
at its center. 
  [Umberto Bossi, Northern League leader] It is a government 
which has remained in office despite the fact that the whole 
country wants change, wants an election. It seems to me that 
consequently a legitimate action is being carried out. It seems 
to me that Ciampi has upheld civil liberties -- he has kept his 
word. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

