<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ankara Views Confidence-Building Measures `Positively' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1301150694 Nicosia Bayrak Radio in Turkish 1130 GMT 13 Jan 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1301150694 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Bayrak Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Hakki Atun has said the Cyprus issue 
is a national cause and his government is determined to wage 
this cause with Turkey. 
  Tugay Ulucevik, Turkish Foreign Ministry deputy under 
secretary; and Ertugrul Atakan, Turkish Foreign Ministry deputy 
director general of Cypriot and Greek affairs; today visited 
Prime Minister Atun; Ozker Ozgur, state minister and deputy 
prime minister; and Atay Ahmet Rasit, foreign affairs and 
defense minister. 
  In a speech during his meeting with the Turkish delegation, 
Prime Minister Atun said the coalition government views the 
Cyprus problem as the priority issue before it. However, he 
said, we are determined to defend the rights of the people 
vigorously while tackling the issue. 
  Tugay Ulucevik briefed the prime minister on Turkey's role 
and attitude in the current stage of the Cyprus problem. 
Ulucevik pointed out that there was a slowdown in efforts to 
reach a solution to the problem due to the early general 
elections. He said the international community expects the 
Cyprus problem to be tackled now that the new government 
received a vote of confidence, adding that the 
confidence-building measures are now on the agenda. As always, 
he stressed, Turkey wants the decision to be reached in Cyprus. 
The Turkish Cypriot and Greek Cypriot people will make their 
own decisions regarding this issue, he added. 
  Ulucevik stated that for a decision to be reached, the 
method 
of free negotiations is essential. That is what Turkey 
believes, he said. 
  Ulucevik pointed out that even though it is up to the 
Turkish 
Republic of Northern Cyprus to decide on the confidence-building 
measures, in principle, Turkey has always looked positively at 
the idea that the two communities should take 
confidence-building measures. In principle, he added, Turkey 
supports this issue. 
  Ulucevik said that in the coming days, the search for a 
solution will focus on this issue between the two communities. 
Naturally, the decision will be made by the Turkish Cypriot 
Government, he said. 
  Speaking at his meeting with Ulucevik and Atakan, Ozker 
Ozgur, state minister and deputy prime minister, said he has 
always been in favor of a solution of the Cyprus problem, which 
has been going on for the past 30 years. The world expects this 
problem to be resolved, he said. 
  Ozgur pointed out that he shares Ulucevik's views on the 
Cyprus problem. He said: The coalition government has a 
positive approach to the solution of the Cyprus problem as soon 
as possible. There is a confidence crisis between the two 
communities created during the past 30 years. The coalition 
government will do all it can to eliminate this. Our government 
wants an acceptable solution. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

