<H3> <TI>   Arianespace To Launch European Weather Satellites </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1101110194 Paris AFP in English 2241 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1101110194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, Jan 10 (AFP) -- Arianespace is to launch the 
next three satellites to be run by the European weather 
satellite service EUMETSAT in the first five years of the next 
century, according to a statement released here Monday [10 
January]. 
  Under a preliminary contract signed Monday, Arianespace will 
launch three satellites in 2001, 2002 and 2005, the EUMETSAT 
statement said. 
  The three Meteosat craft "will offer high performance 
meteological coverage until at least 2012," the statement said. 
  The contracts for the three satellites will be negotiated 
separately "to allow EUMETSAT to benefit from a very competitive 
and attractive commercial situation," EUMETSAT director John 
Morgan said. 
  EUMETSAT was set up in 1986 by 17 countries and provides 
weather satellite services for Europe from its base at 
Darmstadt-Eberstadt near Frankfurt. 

</TEXT>

