<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ruehe, Vargas Urge Reduction in Eurofighter Costs </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1701142394 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1328 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1701142394 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Bonn (DDP/ADN) -- Federal Defense Minister Volker 
Ruehe (Christian Democratic Union) and his Spanish counterpart 
Julian Garcia Vargas have expressed their "determination" to 
force down the price of the planned European fighter. Following 
talks with Vargas, Ruehe told journalists in Bonn today that 
both sides agreed that further savings have to be made relating 
to the cost of the aircraft. 
  Ruehe confirmed that Germany and Spain will need a new 
fighter in the year 2002. The estimated price of each aircraft 
is now about 102 million German marks. This is "still too 
high," Ruehe said. Alongside Germany and Spain, the fighter is 
also being developed by Italy and France. Vargas stressed that 
the aircraft must also be competitive on the world market. 
  According to the ministers, a Spanish armored brigade will 
be 
the first Spanish unit ever to take part in a Eurocorps exercise 
this year. The ministers also talked about the Partnership for 
Peace concept adopted by NATO with the Central and East European 
countries and the CIS states. In this regard, Ruehe referred to 
the Bundeswehr maneuver planned with Poland and Denmark in the 
Baltic Sea, while Vargas talked of Spain's intensive contacts 
with Poland, the Czech Republic, Romania, and Bulgaria. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

