<H3> <TI>   Aktuna Criticizes `Sadistic' Security Forces </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1501170094 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1545 GMT 15 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA1501170094 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Istanbul, Jan. 15 (A.A) -- Government spokesman 
and State Minister Yildirim Aktuna said today that his 
government did not approve of the attitude of security forces 
against the demonstrating public servants two days ago. 
  Many public servants were detained when they attempted to 
protest the government for not recognizing their union rights 
and increasing their salaries very little. The police roughed 
up some of the demonstrators, and the scene was aired by a 
private TV channel the same day. 
  In a press conference, Aktuna said security forces who were 
on duty all over the country had their lives at stake in every 
instance and these were people who were conscious of their job. 
  However, he said, they did not approve of the attitude of 
the 
security forces during the demonstrations. 
  "The importance, seriousness and weight of their duty do not 
justify their sadistic and primitive behavior against our 
people," he said. 
  "The government will make it sure that such behavior will 
not 
be repeated," he said. 

</TEXT>

