<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Spokesman Comments on Skopje Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1701213394 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1230 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1701213394 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Greece is the firm guarantor of peace, security, and 
stability in the Balkans, since it has all the political and 
[word indistinct] advantages. Government spokesman Evangelos 
Venizelos made this statement in response to a question on the 
issue of Skopje following the meeting Lord Owen and Thorvald 
Stoltenberg had yesterday with Foreign Minister Karolos 
Papoulias, who is presiding over the European Union. 
  The spokesman stated that there are no secret talks on this 
issue. He reiterated that Greece's positions are well known, 
adding that Foreign Minister Papoulias will go to the United 
States, where he will outline Greek positions to international 
mediator Cyrus Vance, who has already been briefed by Andonios 
Exarkhos, Greece's permanent representative at the United 
Nations. 
  The government spokesman also repeated that any development 
on the Skopje issue depends on practical signs of goodwill by 
Skopje since, as he stressed, [Macedonian President] Kiro 
Gligorov appears to recognize the importance of good relations 
with Greece. These positions, Venizelos added, are not the 
positions of the government, but those of the Greek Republic, 
which Prime Minister Papandreou outlined in Brussels last week 
at the highest and most critical level, the NATO Summit. As is 
known, U.S. President Bill Clinton, European Union Commission 
President Jacques Delors, and the Greek prime minister, who is 
presiding over the European Union, participated in this summit. 
  The government spokesman was also asked to comment on the 
personal statement of Public Order Minister Stilianos 
Papathemelis, who advocated an offensive if Skopje insists on 
the name Macedonia. The spokesman stressed that the government 
positions are only expressed by the prime minister. He said the 
minister has made it clear that his remarks were personal views. 

</TEXT>

