<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Venizelos Reiterates Government Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1801133994 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1230 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>



<TEXT>
txt}[Text] Government spokesman Evangelos Venizelos today said 
that the Greek foreign policy positions are known, oft repeated, 
and clear in every direction. Venizelos was referring to press 
reports which, he said, imply that Greek policy on Skopje and 
the dialogue is changing. The name is not up for negotiation, 
the government spokesman said. He noted that Skopje must 
believe that it is to its benefit to change the name. The name 
is not subject to negotiation, but becomes an issue of dialogue 
so that the Greek side can expand on its position. 
<F P=103> NC1801133994 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
 Language: <F P=105>Greek and clear </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  Answering questions, Venizelos said the government considers 
acceptance of such a proposal possible and noted that he is 
under the impression that the Greek side's statements are not 
falling on deaf ears. The government spokesman pointed out that 
there has been no move from the government's positions and 
repeated that no country will be recognized with the name 
Macedonia or its derivatives. He added that the government 
expects tangible and practical signs from Skopje that would 
diminish its intransigence and provocation. 
  Replying to other questions, he said Greece agreed to 
Skopje's application to join the United Nations as the Former 
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia, which came up during the New 
Democracy's term in power. Asked about the level of dialogue 
with Skopje, Venizelos said it is too early to say anything and 
added that the process is still pending at the United Nations. 
It is within that framework that Foreign Minister Karolos 
Papoulias sent a letter. The government spokesman noted that 
the previous government was characterized by double talk, while 
this government tells everyone the same things. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

