<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Atun, UN Officials Discuss Confidence Measures </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1401164794 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1545 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA1401164794 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Lefkosa [Nicosia], Jan 14 (AA) -- Prime Minister 
Hakki Atun of the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus (TRNC) 
said on Friday [14 January] that his country will announce its 
views on confidence building measures after discussing the issue 
together with Turkish officials. 
  Prime minister of the coalition government and Democratic 
Party leader Atun, speaking after a meeting with Gustave 
Feissel, the United Nations deputy special envoy to Cyprus, said 
Feissel conveyed the UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali's 
recent offers on the issue. 
  Atun said Greek Cypriots had a negative approach to the 
confidence building measures, adding that their negative 
approach affected the process of talks. 
  Feissel said their aim was to provide a peaceful and lasting 
solution to the Cyprus problem. 
  Meanwhile TRNC foreign minister who is also acting as 
defense 
minister Atay Ahmet Rasit criticized the coming of Greek 
commandos to the island saying Greek Cypriots' military 
initiations hampered confidence measures. 

</TEXT>

