<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ahtisaari, Rehn Win First Round of Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1601204694 Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network in Finnish 
1940 GMT 16 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1601204694 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Finnish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Martti Ahtisaari and Elisabeth Rehn are going 
forward to the second round of the elections. Martti Ahtisaari 
has 25.9 percent of the votes, Elisabeth Rehn 22 percent, Paavo 
Vaeyrynen 19.5 percent, and Raimo Ilaskivi 15.5 percent. Then 
there are the other candidates. There is quite a big gap to the 
next one, Keijo Korhonen, with 5.8 percent; Claes Andersson with 
3.8 percent; Pertti Virtanen 3 percent; Eeva Kuuskoski 2.6 
percent; Toimi Kankaanniemi and Sulo Aittoniemi, both with 1 
percent; and Pekka Tiainen with 0.2 percent. 
  Looking at the absolute number of votes, perhaps they will 
stay in some people's minds. Martti Ahtisaari received just 
over 800,000 votes in these elections, Elisabeth Rehn 700,000 
votes, Paavo Vaeyrynen just over 600,000, and Raimo Ilaskivi 
nearly 500,000. At a rough glance, there are just over 1 
million votes to be distributed in the second round of the 
elections, if we assume that everybody sticks to their 
candidates in the first round, that is Ahtisaari and Rehn. 

</TEXT>

