<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rehn Leads in Opinion Polls </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1601213294 Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network in Finnish 
2100 GMT 16 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1601213294 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Finnish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Elisabeth Rehn of the Swedish People's Party 
turned the first round of the presidential elections into 
something of a thriller. In the vote count, she climbed to 
second place after the Social Democrats' Martti Ahtisaari, which 
means that Ahtisaari and Rehn will meet in the second round of 
elections in three weeks. According to the latest opinion polls, 
Rehn will defeat Ahtisaari and be elected president. 
  Ahtisaari polled 25.9 percent of the votes in the first 
round 
of the elections, and Rehn polled 22 percent. Paavo Vaeyrynen 
of the Center was third with 19.5 percent of the votes and Raimo 
Ilaskivi of the Coalition was fourth with 15.2 percent. The 
election turnout was 78.4 percent. 
  Elisabeth Rehn secured nearly four times more votes than the 
Swedish People's Party normally polls in a Diet election. She 
polled about 700,000 votes, while Ahtisaari polled about 
826,000. Rehn outdistanced Vaeyrynen by over 78,000 votes. 
  Elisabeth Rehn secured the majority of today's votes, 26.7 
percent, and 15.5 percent of the postal votes. Ahtisaari polled 
24.9 percent of today's votes, and 27.2 percent of the postal 
votes. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

