<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   _o_ Media Notes: Evolving Chirac-Balladur Relationship </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94P20224B </F>
<F P=103> 94P20224B </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:CSO 

  [Editorial Report] According to Philippe Reinhard's article 
in the 3 January Paris center-right daily LE QUOTIDIEN DE PARIS, 
Prime Minister Edouard Balladur's most delicate task for 1994 
will be dealing with Jacques Chirac, leader of Balladur's own 
party, the Rally for the Republic (RPR), in a probable race for 
the succession to President Francois Mitterrand in 1995. In the 
"inevitable" struggle that will ensue, Chirac enjoys two 
important advantages, says Reinhard. He can count on a devoted 
political apparatus and, unlike a Balladur busy with day-to-day 
problems and bound by his own promise to postpone the opening of 
the presidential debate, he enjoys greater freedom of movement. 
For his part, Balladur does not lack trump cards, Reinhard 
continues. The prime minister is already considered a candidate 
by a number of political personalities of the parliamentary 
majority and enjoys popular support, as indicated in a series of 
polls. However, the outcome of a race is undecided, Reinhard 
points out. Both men must take into account those who prefer to 
wait--like Minister of Foreign Affairs Alain Juppe--and those 
"lurking in the background," such as Union for French Democracy 
(UDF) leader Valery Giscard d'Estaing, who hopes that a 
Chirac-Balladur confrontation will open a "window of 
opportunity" for himself. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

