<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EC Commissioner Cited on Single European Currency </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1801172294 Paris AFP in English 1610 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1801172294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Strasbourg, Jan 18 (AFP) -- The European Community 
can progress towards the introduction of a single currency 
without reimposing narrow bands on the exchange rate mechanism 
(ERM), Finance Commissioner Henning Christophersen said on 
Tuesday [18 January]. 
  "If everybody accepts that the 15 percent band is a normal 
band, the only important question is: Is your currency close to 
the central rate?," he told journalists outside a meeting of the 
European parliament. 
  At the beginning of August, in the face of massive 
speculation against currencies in the European monetary system 
(EMS) and particularly against the French franc, EC finance 
ministers widened the permitted range of fluctuation of most of 
the currencies within the ERM from 2.25 percent to 15 percent. 
  Christophersen said that the re-imposition of narrow bands 
might lead to a resumption of speculation against ERM currencies. 
  Under the terms of the Maastricht Treaty, the Community is 
to 
begin stage three of economic and monetary union between the end 
of 1997 and the end of 1999 at the latest. 
  Under stage three the Community is to adopt a single 
currency, and Christophersen declined to rule out the 
possibility that the currency might be adopted in 1997. 
However, he said that it would be "very, very difficult." 
  A senior EC official has said that six members of the 
Community might be ready quickly to meet the conditions for use 
of a single currency. He named them as Belgium, Luxembourg, the 
Netherlands, Germany, Ireland and France. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

