<F P=100> AUSTRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Busek, Vranitzky Disagree on NATO `Partnership' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1801153394 Vienna DIE PRESSE in German 18 Jan 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> AU1801153394 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna DIE PRESSE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report signed "d.h.": "Busek: Sympathy for NATO </F>
Partnership"] 
  [Text] Vienna -- Austrian People's Party [OeVP] Chairman 
and Vice Chancellor Erhard Busek on 17 January welcomed more 
clearly than last week the Partnership for Peace program offered 
by NATO. This means that he disagrees with Austrian Chancellor 
Franz Vranitzky, who in a DIE PRESSE interview rejected 
Austria's participation in such partnership. Commenting on the 
statements of the head of government and chairman of the Social 
Democratic Party of Austria [SPOe], Busek said: "This is not 
the government's opinion!" 
  The OeVP chairman said: "We welcome this initiative. 
Undoubtedly, there is no alternative to it." Busek said that 
all the other [heads of] neutral European states "except for 
Vranitzky" have welcomed the initiative. 
<H3>  Austrian Trade Union Federation Recommendation on the 
European Union </H3>
  Austrian Trade Union Federation [OeGB] President 
Verzetnitsch 
announced a separate OeGB recommendation for a referendum on 
European Union (EU) membership. This recommendation will be 
discussed at a conference at the end of the membership 
negotiations. 
  Representatives of the two government parties on 17 January 
demonstrated cautious optimism that the membership negotiations 
would be completed by March. SPOe floor leader Fuhrmann 
considers a date in March "not totally unrealistic." OeVP 
Secretary General Molterer believes the odds in favor are "more 
than 50 percent." 

</TEXT>

